'''Idabelle Smith Firestone''' (November 10, 1874 – July 7, 1954) was an American [[composer]] and [[songwriter]].<ref name=obit/>
==Biography== She was born in [[Minnesota City, Minnesota]] on November 10, 1874.<ref>ASCAP Biographical Dictionary. Fourth edition. Compiled for the American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers by Jaques Cattell Press. New York: R.R. Bowker, 1980. [ASCAP 4]</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Uncommon Friends: Life with Thomas Edison, Henry Ford, Harvey Firestone, Alexis Carrel, and Charles Lindbergh|author=James Newton|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|year=1989|isbn= 9780156926201|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=trtC3yH8bI4C&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=idabelle+firestone+bio&source=bl&ots=X9nXDssEhi&sig=SHmyZ0D_Y2M7zAx7B9xMfkjGOVc&hl=en&ei=vzzjSZvJG6LulQexx8XgDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9#PPA42,M1}}</ref> She was educated at [[Alma College (St. Thomas, Ontario)|Alma College]], [[Ontario]]. Her father, George, held the patent to a [[flour]] milling process.
On 20 November 1895, she married [[Harvey Samuel Firestone]], who had begun the [[Firestone Tire and Rubber Company]] five years earlier.<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~mysong/p11749.htm "Shirer Family Genealogy Project" ''ancestry.com''] 18 October 2010</ref> She was the mother of [[Harvey S. Firestone, Jr.]], and [[Leonard Firestone]], the grandmother of [[Brooks Firestone]], and the great-grandmother of [[William Clay Ford, Jr.]], [[Andrew Firestone]], and [[Nick Firestone]].
She joined the [[ASCAP]] in 1948. Her compositions include "[[If I Could Tell You (song)|If I Could Tell You]]" (the theme of "[[Voice of Firestone]]" programs), "In My Garden", "You Are the Song in My Heart", "Do You Recall?", "Melody of Love" and "Bluebirds".<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1342341/bio "Idabelle Firestone" ''imdb.com'']</ref>
She died on July 7, 1954.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Mrs. Harvey Firestone Sr. Dead. Tire Manufacturer's Widow, 79, She Composed Two Theme Songs for the Company's Musical Radio Show |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1954/07/08/archives/mrs-harvey-firestone-sr-dead-tire-manufacturers-widow-79-she.html |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=July 8, 1954 |accessdate=2015-04-23 }}</ref>
